  data-post-sentiment-totals="{&quot;agree&quot;:&quot;3&quot;,&quot;interesting&quot;:&quot;5&quot;,&quot;funny&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;addsto&quot;:&quot;2&quot;,&quot;disagree&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;inaccurate&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;pointless&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;abusive&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}">
  
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="wirrbeltier"><a href="/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&u=822785" rel="nofollow">wirrbeltier</a></span><span class="rank">Smack-Fu Master, in training</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
          <a href="?comments=1&amp;post=40807382&amp;mode=quote#reply" class='quotelink icon' rel='nofollow' title="Reply">reply</a>
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/04/ipcc-report-the-next-few-years-are-critical/?comments=1&post=40807382#comment-40807382" title="2022-04-05T23:47:24+00:00" class="timeago datetime" rel="nofollow">Tue Apr 05, 2022 6:47 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40807209#p40807209" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Lonyo</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">One potential positive of gas price spikes and then Russia's decision to go to war is that people are more acutely aware that relying on unstable regimes for supplies of key resources isn't such a great idea, and reducing volatility and increasing energy security is a good plan.<br /><br />Even if Europe is heading to greener energy, doing it faster becomes key to reduce dependence on Russia, and replacing coal with gas is less of a stop gap solution when your gas supplies are expensive and from Russia.<br /><br />It turns it from a climate issue to a national security one which might get everyone on the same page and supporting action, even if it's for the &quot;wrong&quot; reasons.</div><br /><br />Ironically, it looks like Putin might just have earmarked Russia's fossil infrastructure for the first wave of fossil write-offs (from a western perspective at least, maybe China grabs the chance to buy all the capacity at firesale prices). It may very well be in the western fossil fuel industry's short-term interest (write-offs on projects in Russia nonwithstanding).<br /><br />Then again, this took the combined political will of the western world, in an acute crisis, across most of the political spectrum. <br /><br />However, even if the Russian petro-kleptocracy collapses and Gazprom never pumps another cubic meter of gas again, this means there is still way too much infrastructure pumping way too much fossil carbon out of the ground elsewhere in the world. At some point, the next wave of write-offs will hit western producers directly, and many of those companies are richer and have more political influence than small nation states. I wonder whether western democracies (let alone emerging autocracies such as china) are up to the task. <br /><br />As an example, consider that (IIRC) many US frackers were not competetive on the world market for most of the late 2010s. They might have just gotten another lease of life, but they don't have the capital structure or know-how to expand into anything other than hydrocarbons, and are running out of time fast. Maybe a smart US government should kickstart an &quot;Drill rigs to windmills&quot; capacity-building program to offer them an off-ramp, so as to defuse the threat to democracy posed by a mighty industry fighting for the survival of its business model.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=822785">wirrbeltier</a> on Tue Apr 05, 2022 7:18 pm</p>
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <span class="userinfo">22 posts | reg. <time class="reg-date">Jun 22, 2020</time></span>
