    <div class="body">
      So basically we'll end up with a long slow change to renewables that's going to take as long as it takes and no great urgency.<br />We'll end up with 3-3.5degrees, some rasied ocean and a fairly different and hotter climate. But slowly we'll change how we produce food and items, how we travel and how we live. There will be lots more people moving away from too-dry-too-warm zones and it's going to cause some raised instability in some regions and the right wing will use xenophobia to get votes. Things will get climatically worse but we'll live. Coral reefs will disappear.<br /><br />When I was in my home country a few summers ago my family went to a bronze age spot that had been used for boats. It was about 20m higher then the current wheat fields a bit further out in the 'valley'. I was thinking about how different the landscape is now. But people have lived on.
      
    </div>
