<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment star read"
  data-post-negative="-13"
  data-post-positive="60"
  data-user-vote="neutral"
  data-post-id="40807463"
  data-poster-id="64419"
  id="comment-40807463"
  
  data-user-sentiment="neutral"
  
  data-post-sentiment-totals="{&quot;agree&quot;:&quot;17&quot;,&quot;interesting&quot;:&quot;7&quot;,&quot;funny&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;addsto&quot;:&quot;6&quot;,&quot;disagree&quot;:&quot;2&quot;,&quot;inaccurate&quot;:&quot;2&quot;,&quot;pointless&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;abusive&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}">
  
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Kethinov"><a href="/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&u=64419" rel="nofollow">Kethinov</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
          <a href="?comments=1&amp;post=40807463&amp;mode=quote#reply" class='quotelink icon' rel='nofollow' title="Reply">reply</a>
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/04/ipcc-report-the-next-few-years-are-critical/?comments=1&post=40807463#comment-40807463" title="2022-04-06T00:17:27+00:00" class="timeago datetime" rel="nofollow">Tue Apr 05, 2022 7:17 pm</a>
        
          <span class="highlight reader-fav">Reader Fav</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      It's super unhelpful to say things like &quot;we're fucked&quot; or &quot;extinction event.&quot; That's not what's happening. Some people even go so far as to say all of humanity is existentially threatened by this or that the planet will suffer a runaway greenhouse effect like Venus. This hyperbole is very harmful.<br /><br />It's important to be specific about what the consequences will actually be. Some regions will benefit. Many more will become uninhabitable. There will be a very slow, but very significant increase in migration and immigration to more mild climates due to climate change wrecking places and people wanting to leave. There will be some direct and many more indirect deaths. It is indeed a tragedy, and a preventable one.<br /><br />But it is not an existential threat to civilization. And our lack of political will to deal with it is nothing more than a reflection of our broader unwillingness to deal with most social problems like homelessness and poverty. The poor will suffer the costs of climate change. Most everybody else will adapt and they'll be fine. Most people know that's the path we're on and that's why nobody sees this as an urgent problem that requires extraordinary intervention.<br /><br />If we can't even house the homeless, why the fuck should we expect society to worry about an increase in climate refugees diffusely spread out across decades? We will only see real action on climate change if the problem gets severe enough that it starts somehow threatening middle class people in a direct, obvious way.<br /><br />Meanwhile talking about how the world is gonna end just makes those people even more checked out than they already are. Hyperbole is poison in politics. Say what you actually mean. Be specific, and accurate.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=64419">Kethinov</a> on Tue Apr 05, 2022 7:20 pm</p>
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <span class="userinfo">1951 posts | reg. <time class="reg-date">Dec 20, 2003</time></span>
    </footer>
  </li>

