    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40807373#p40807373" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Ziv</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40807331#p40807331" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">sigmasirrus</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So what’s the worst case scenario? What would be the effects?</div><br />The sea level that has been rising about 2mm a year for the past 150 years may rise more like 3 mm a year.</div> <br />In other words, 80% of the urban populations will have to invest trillions every decade in flood-management to control storm surges and high tides damage in cities. Just NYC might spend 50 billion over the next decade on this.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Some areas that received X amount of rain will receive 0.75X rain in the future. Other areas will get more rain rather than less.</div> <br />And thus the changing patterns will mean floods where the infrastructure to address them isn't present, destroying cities and crops, and farming communities will face drought in the large swaths of the world as the aquifers are depleted and populations fail to adapt to drier conditions.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Winter temps will rise a degree or two. Summer temps will rise a bit less.</div> <br />Snowpack will disappear, compounding drought conditions for the poorest who can't invest in water management. Farmers will rise up against the failure of their governments to offer them a life like their parents had, while rising food prices will force the poor into more desperation. Money spent in securing food will increase for vast swaths of the population, leading to societal upheaval. Demagogues will leverage this and stir up strongman rule and jingoism. <br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">A hundred mile swath of permafrost will melt seasonally. </div> <br />Contributing to increase CO2 emissions and increased hopelessness. These new territories will not be agriculturally productive, and the millions of refugees from small wars won't be welcomed or able to build a new life.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The North West passage will be open a bit more often. </div> <br />But this won't be followed by an increase in polar commerce, since Russia and China have decoupled themselves from the West. Asian democracies like Japan and Europe do increase commercial ties as a result.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">People in the north will tend to have a better growing season and do better in many ways. </div> <br />Or not. Climate instability means growing seasons are stunted by storms, unseasonal weather, and end up worse. Especially if the rest of the world is slow-burning towards small wars and societal upheaval.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">People in the south will tend to have too much heat and their seasonal changes will be for the worse. </div> <br />But the rise of neo-fascists will make sure the poor can't migrate, and ensure humanity loses the progress in making lives better for everybody achieved in the past 5 decades. Expect an increase in never-ending wars in the third world.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Ziv wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The news will still be full of predictions of disasters just a decade away. </div> <br />As disasters become more and more frequent and people become detached from them. The U.S. keeps adding new records to the <a href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/744015/most-expensive-natural-disasters-usa/" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">list of top 10 most expensive disasters</a><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And if we don't act this moment in ways that will damage our economy in ways too numerous to mention, well, life will be he## and the only life on the planet in a few years will be cockroaches. Yes, I know that I predicted that global warming would severely damage the earth in just a few years back in 2000, and again in 2010, and so far it hasn't happened, but someday it just might! <br />Maybe?<br /></div><br />Climate-change denialist will keep fighting with strawmen. Because they got theirs, f the rest.<br /><br />Edit: fix broken URL.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=798067">LongTimeLurker629</a> on Wed Apr 06, 2022 11:41 am</p>
      
