      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40807210#p40807210" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Imbrium</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I get tired of reading these reports, because the world has made it blindingly clear that no one is going to take the steps necessary to change the trajectory of things. Politicians nod their heads sagely, promising to undertake bold initiatives to deal with climate change, and then little, if anything happens.</div><br />I'm sorry but that's bullshit. A large number of people and politicians are taking steps.<br /><br />There are individual people (like me), business/corporations, and even some governments who are working towards net zero by 2030 which is two decades earlier than the general consensus for when the world needs to be net zero. If enough people can achieve these goals, we'll keep emissions down to a reasonable level.<br /><br />Not enough have that goal right now - but you shouldn't say nobody is acting when people are. We're making big sacrifices and those shouldn't be ignored. Become one of us yourself. Put pressure on other people to join you.<br /><br />Vote for politicians who are acting or who would act if they were elected - even if they don't win the next election, whoever does will see the vote distribution it will influence their decisions. Two thirds of Americans think the government isn't doing enough according to poling. That's a lot of people - enough to have a substantial influence on decisions if even a small percentage demonstrate a willingness to change how they vote based on this issue.
      
